<section class="section section--alt" id="6000-83-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Error 6000, 83, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Error 6000, 83 appears when QuickBooks Desktop can&rsquo;t open or restore the company file. You most often see it when the file is stored on a server or network share, when you&rsquo;re restoring a backup, or when the Windows folder holding the file has the wrong permissions. The error is QuickBooks telling you it reached for the file and the access failed &mdash; whether that&rsquo;s a permissions problem on the file&rsquo;s location, a hosting or .ND-file issue in a multi-user setup, a restore pointed at a network drive, or genuine damage to the file.</p>
      <p>The good news is that Error 6000, 83 is highly fixable, and the self-fix steps below work in order of likelihood &mdash; running QuickBooks Tool Hub (Quick Fix My File, then File Doctor) resolves it in many cases before deeper troubleshooting is needed. If self-fix doesn&rsquo;t resolve it, the error recurs, or a multi-user setup won&rsquo;t stabilize, a Certified ProAdvisor diagnostic identifies the deeper cause &mdash; typically permissions, hosting configuration, or file-integrity damage past the documented surface steps. Error 6000, 83 is a QuickBooks Desktop and Enterprise error; it does not appear in QuickBooks Online.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

